\begin_layout Standard
Assume we have 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 (say in 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{2}\left(\left[a,b\right]^{d}\right)$
\end_inset

) that we want to approximate.
 A straightforward method of approximating this function is to use tensor
 product basis functions (e.g.
 a Fourier series),
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f\left(z_{1},z_{2},\dots z_{d}\right)\simeq\sum_{i_{1}=1}^{N_{1}}\dots\sum_{i_{d}=1}^{N_{d}}c_{i_{1},\dots,i_{d}}\phi_{i_{1}}\left(z_{1}\right)\phi_{i_{2}}\left(z_{j}\right)\dots\phi_{i_{d}}\left(z_{d}\right).
\]

\end_inset

Bad idea! The number of coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{i_{1}\dots i_{d}}$
\end_inset

 grows exponentially w.r.t 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

.
 This is the 
\color red
Curse of Dimensionality
\color inherit
.
 
