\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Unfortunately, unlike the SVD, the best rank 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 CTD approximation to a tensor does not always exist (space of rank 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 tensors isn't closed).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Computations of CTDs based on ALS algorithms don't always find a global
 minimum in terms of approximation error.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A different tensor decomposition, the Tucker decomposition,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{U}=\sum_{l_{1}=1}^{r_{\mathbf{1}}}\dots\sum_{l_{d}=1}^{r_{\mathbf{d}}}s_{l_{1},\dots,l_{d}}\mathbf{U}_{1}^{l_{1}}\otimes\dots\otimes\mathbf{U}_{d}^{l_{d}}
\]

\end_inset

does not suffer from the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

closure problem.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Curse of Dimensionality again: number of 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{l_{1},\dots l_{d}}$
\end_inset

 grows exponentially with 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
