\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
A method for generating separated representations from scattered data was
 introduced by [Beylkin et.
 al 2009].
 To form the separated representation,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g\left(\mathbf{x}\right)=\sum_{l=1}^{r}s_{l}\prod_{i=1}^{d}g_{i}\left(x_{i}\right),
\]

\end_inset

a sequence of one dimensional problems are solved.
 To form the one-dimensional subproblems compute,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{j}^{l}=s_{l}\prod_{i=2}^{d}g_{i}^{l}\left(x_{i}^{j}\right),
\]

\end_inset

for the sample indices 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 and rank terms 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 and minimize the residual
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{j=1}^{N}\left(y_{j}-\sum_{l=1}^{r}p_{j}^{l}g_{1}^{l}\left(x_{1}^{j}\right)\right)^{2},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

-th data value.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Separator

\end_layout

\begin_layout PlainFrame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Functional approximations in separated form continued
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
To solve the minimization problem (assuming 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

's are polynomials of fixed order) first form the standard Vandermonde matrix,
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V\left(i,j\right)=\phi_{i}\left(x_{j}\right),\,\,\,\, i=0,\dots,M\,\,\textrm{and}\,\, j=1,\dots,N,
\]

\end_inset

then form the following block matrix,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A=\left[P_{1}V,P_{2}V,\dots,P_{r}V\right],
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P_{l}=\textrm{diag}\left(p_{1}^{l},\dots,p_{N-1}^{l}\right),
\]

\end_inset

and solve the linear system,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A\mathbf{c}=\mathbf{y},
\]

\end_inset

for the coefficients of 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}^{l}\left(x_{1}\right)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $l=1,\dots r$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Separator

\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Remarks on functional approximations
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
This residual is then minimized for the other directions, 
\begin_inset Formula $i=2,\dots d$
\end_inset

, similar to an ALS sweep.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If the error is not sufficiently small, perform another sweep.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If the sweeps are not changing the error by a significant amount, increase
 the rank 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 and continue sweeps
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The functions 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{i}$
\end_inset

 are typically of some predetermined form, e.g.
 polynomials of fixed order (see [Beylkin et al.
 2009] and [Doostan et al.
 2013]), but there are other posibilities (wavelets, exponentials, Gaussians,
 rational functions, etc.).
\end_layout

\end_deeper
