\begin_layout Subsection
Building a SR via Tensor Train
\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Sketch of the functional approximation algorithms using TT
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
The idea behind using tensor-train to generate functional representations
 is to,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Construct a tensor product grid from Gaussian quadratures.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Evaluate the weighted target function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 at the quadrature points; this forms a tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{B}=f\left(\mathbf{X}\right)\sqrt{\mathbf{W}}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Approximate the tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{B}$
\end_inset

 with a tensor train approximation,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\Vert \mathbf{B}-\mathbf{B}_{TT}\right\Vert _{F}\le\epsilon\left\Vert \mathbf{B}\right\Vert _{F},
\]

\end_inset

for this step use either TT-SVD, TT-cross, or TT-DMRG-cross.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The TT cores of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{B}_{TT}$
\end_inset

 are used as a discretized version of the cores of the functional tensor-train,
 automatically leading to the following approximation of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\Vert f-f_{TT}\right\Vert _{L_{\mu}^{2}}\lesssim\epsilon\left\Vert f\right\Vert _{L_{\mu}^{2}}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Separator

\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Sketch of the functional approximation algorithms using TT
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
From the functional tensor-train approximation of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{TT}$
\end_inset

, there are two options:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Project 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{TT}$
\end_inset

 onto a polynomial basis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Use 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{TT}$
\end_inset

 to generate a Lagrange interpolation from candidate points.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To get to these options let us first understand the connection between 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{B}_{TT}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{TT}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{TT}$
\end_inset

 is defined as,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f_{TT}\left(\mathbf{x}\right):=\sum_{\alpha_{0},\dots,\alpha_{d}}^{\mathbf{r}}\gamma_{1}\left(\alpha_{0},x_{1},\alpha_{1}\right)\dots\gamma_{d}\left(\alpha_{d-1},x_{d},\alpha_{d}\right).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Separator

\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Relationship between the DTT and FTT
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f_{TT}\left(\mathbf{x}\right):=\sum_{\alpha_{0},\dots,\alpha_{d}}^{\mathbf{r}}\gamma_{1}\left(\alpha_{0},x_{1},\alpha_{1}\right)\dots\gamma_{d}\left(\alpha_{d-1},x_{d},\alpha_{d}\right).
\]

\end_inset

And recalling that the tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{B}$
\end_inset

, approximated by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{B}_{TT}$
\end_inset

, was generated from weighted samples of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{A}_{TT}=\mathbf{B}_{TT}/\sqrt{\mathbf{W}}=\sum_{\alpha_{0},\dots,\alpha_{d}}^{\mathbf{r}}G_{1}\left(\alpha_{0},i_{1},\alpha_{1}\right)\dots G_{d}\left(\alpha_{d-1},i_{d},\alpha_{d}\right)
\]

\end_inset

is 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{TT}$
\end_inset

 evaluated on the tensor product grid of quadrature nodes.
 From these samples it is straightforward to,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
compute projections onto polynomial bases.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
use linear or Lagrange interpolation.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Separator

\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Projection onto polynomial bases
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
To compute the projection 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{\mathbf{N}}f_{TT}=\sum_{\mathbf{i}=0}^{\mathbf{N}}\tilde{c}_{\mathbf{i}}\Phi_{\mathbf{i}}$
\end_inset

 evaluate,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
